	<section class="page">
<p>Ever heard of Homebrew? It’s a package manager with a very unusual feature. It allows ordinary users to install packages without using <strong>sudo,</strong> and it’s available for both macOS and Linux. While the tool on each of these systems is referred to as Homebrew, the Linux version installs as linuxbrew.</p><p>Once installed, users can use Homebrew via the <strong>brew</strong> command to install packages very easily. Installation of Homebrew itself, however, does generally require <a href="https://www.networkworld.com/article/3236499/some-tricks-for-using-sudo.html"><strong>sudo</strong> </a>privileges and installs in /home/linuxbrew.</p><p>The man page for the <strong>brew</strong> command calls it “The Missing Package Manager for macOS (or Linux)”.</p><p class="jumpTag"><a href="/article/3636149/installing-packages-on-linux-and-mac-with-homebrew.html#jump">To read this article in full, please click here</a></p></section></article>